}
@article{Sillero2010a,
abstract = {Hyla meridionalis occurs in North Africa, South-western Europe, Madeira, Menorca and Canary Islands. The species may currently be in expansion in Salamanca and Madrid where new records were observed recently. Northern Iberia, southern France and Canarian populations may come from northern Morocco by human introduction. The global distribution of the species was modelled in order to determine the potential distribution in a current and a future environment scenario. In order to simulate the expansion process from south to north and verify the effects of modelling a dynamic and disequilibrium situation, the species records were split in four samples: records only from North Africa, from North Africa plus South Iberian Peninsula, from North Africa and all the Iberian Peninsula, and from the whole distribution. In the current scenario, a model was produced for each sample; in the future scenario only one model for the global distribution. Models were developed with Maximum Entropy, which uses presence-only occurrence data. The models were compared per pairs by the Cohen's Kappa. The current and future scenario models suggested the species is occupying almost all the suitable areas available in the Mediterranean basin. The species could be in a static and equilibrium situation or the expansion process could be almost completed. Regions considered as suitable outside Mediterranean basin have similar climates to the Mediterranean and Atlantic ones.},
