@article{Skidmore2009,
abstract = {Climatic fluctuations during glacial and interglacial periods in the Pleistocene have greatly modified the distribution of Boreal organisms. One direct effect related to these distribution shifts is that, on the edge of the range of these species, populations exist in isolated patches of suitable habitats with the majority of the area being less suitable. Isolated populations in marginal habitats are vulnerable to several factors including stochastic, climate change and anthropogenic threats. We used historical records of the presence of the smooth snake C. austriaca coupled with remote sensing data including elevation, slope, and climatic variables to develop habitat-suitability models with the Ecological-Niche Factor Analysis in the southernmost limit of its distribution range in the Iberian Peninsula. Results indicated that the distribution of C. austriaca in the Iberian Peninsula is associated with areas with high slope and precipitation, low temperatures, and reduced seasonality in temperature and precipitation. At a broad scale, the areas classified as highly suitable for the species in the southern Iberian Peninsula were small and fragmented. At a local scale, extensive field work demonstrated that C. austriaca have low population densities in these areas. In addition, we detected several human-induced threats including habitat loss motivated by temperature increase and rainfall reduction. Several life-history traits as dietary specialization and reproductive frequency also cooperate to make these populations more vulnerable to local extinctions. Although the highly-suitable southernmost areas are included in protected reserves, specific guidelines for management are needed to assess effective conservation.},
